How can I preview this using github as storage for the code


Thought for 6s
Use GitHub Pages. It is the easiest way to preview a static HTML/CSS/JS site directly from a GitHub repository. GitHub Pages hosts static files from your repo and looks for an entry file like index.html. 

Here’s the simplest way:

Create a new GitHub repository.

Upload your website files into it.

Make sure your main page is named index.html and sits at the top level of the repo, unless you deliberately publish from a /docs folder. GitHub Pages expects an entry file such as index.html. 

In the repo, open Settings → Pages.

Under Build and deployment, choose Deploy from a branch.

Select your branch, usually main, and choose / (root) if your index.html is in the repo root.

Save.

GitHub will publish the site and give you a live link under Pages → Visit site. GitHub says publishing can take up to about 10 minutes after you push changes. 

Your preview URL will usually look like:

https://yourusername.github.io/repository-name/
For a special user site repo named exactly yourusername.github.io, the URL becomes:

https://yourusername.github.io/
GitHub’s quickstart documents both patterns. 

For your current FRVB homepage, the easiest setup is:

create a repo, maybe frvb-website

put the full code in a file called index.html

go to Settings > Pages

publish from main branch, root folder

Then every time you edit and push the file, the live preview updates after GitHub rebuilds it. 

A couple of practical tips:

If you later split your code into index.html, style.css, and script.js, GitHub Pages will still work fine because it serves static files directly from the repo. 

If you ever use a generator or custom build process, GitHub also supports publishing with GitHub Actions instead of directly from a branch. 

If you want, I can give you the exact folder structure and step-by-step upload flow for your FRVB code so you can get it live in one go.


Alright I see how it looks like, first off can you tell me how I can manually make the ball on the website an actuall volleyball?

Yes — the easiest manual way is to replace the current simple ball SVG with a more realistic volleyball SVG.

Right now your ball is basically:

one circle

a gray gradient

a few blue curved lines

That gives “ball icon” more than “real volleyball.”

To make it look like an actual volleyball, you have 3 main options:

Option 1: Improve the existing inline SVG
This is the best option if you want it to stay sharp, scalable, and easy to style.

What to change:

use a warmer white/light cream base instead of plain gray

add stronger panel curves

add more seams, not just 4 lines

add highlight and shadow

add a subtle outer shadow so it feels 3D

In your code, find this part:

<div class="volleyball">
  <svg viewBox="0 0 200 200" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
    ...
  </svg>
</div>
Then replace it with something more realistic like this:

<div class="volleyball">
  <svg viewBox="0 0 300 300" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" aria-hidden="true">
    <defs>
      <radialGradient id="ballBase" cx="35%" cy="30%" r="65%">
        <stop offset="0%" stop-color="#ffffff"/>
        <stop offset="55%" stop-color="#f3f3f0"/>
        <stop offset="100%" stop-color="#cfcfc9"/>
      </radialGradient>

      <radialGradient id="ballShade" cx="70%" cy="75%" r="60%">
        <stop offset="0%" stop-color="rgba(0,0,0,0)"/>
        <stop offset="100%" stop-color="rgba(0,0,0,0.18)"/>
      </radialGradient>

      <filter id="ballShadow" x="-30%" y="-30%" width="160%" height="160%">
        <feDropShadow dx="0" dy="18" stdDeviation="12" flood-color="rgba(0,0,0,0.35)"/>
      </filter>
    </defs>

    <g filter="url(#ballShadow)">
      <circle cx="150" cy="150" r="138" fill="url(#ballBase)"/>

      <!-- blue panels -->
      <path d="M150 15 C195 45 220 95 220 150 C220 205 195 255 150 285"
            fill="none" stroke="#003DA5" stroke-width="10" stroke-linecap="round"/>
      <path d="M150 15 C105 45 80 95 80 150 C80 205 105 255 150 285"
            fill="none" stroke="#003DA5" stroke-width="10" stroke-linecap="round"/>
      <path d="M15 150 C45 108 95 88 150 88 C205 88 255 108 285 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#003DA5" stroke-width="10" stroke-linecap="round"/>
      <path d="M15 150 C45 192 95 212 150 212 C205 212 255 192 285 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#003DA5" stroke-width="10" stroke-linecap="round"/>

      <!-- extra panel seams -->
      <path d="M55 55 C95 78 120 112 128 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#1b4fb8" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.9"/>
      <path d="M245 55 C205 78 180 112 172 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#1b4fb8" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.9"/>
      <path d="M55 245 C95 222 120 188 128 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#1b4fb8" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.9"/>
      <path d="M245 245 C205 222 180 188 172 150"
            fill="none" stroke="#1b4fb8" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.9"/>

      <!-- highlight -->
      <ellipse cx="105" cy="92" rx="42" ry="22" fill="rgba(255,255,255,0.45)" transform="rotate(-20 105 92)"/>

      <!-- rim -->
      <circle cx="150" cy="150" r="138" fill="none" stroke="rgba(0,0,0,0.12)" stroke-width="4"/>
    </g>
  </svg>
</div>
That alone will make it feel much more like a real volleyball.

Option 2: Use a transparent PNG or WebP of a volleyball
This is easiest if you want realism fast.

Replace the SVG with:

<div class="volleyball">
  <img src="volleyball.png" alt="Volleyball">
</div>
Then style it:

.volleyball img {
  width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  display: block;
  filter: drop-shadow(0 20px 30px rgba(0,0,0,0.35));
}
This is good if:

you already have a nice volleyball image

you want photorealism quickly

But it is less flexible than SVG.

Option 3: Use an SVG file made in Figma or Illustrator
This is the cleanest “designer” method.

Process:

draw or import a realistic volleyball in Figma/Illustrator

export as SVG

paste the SVG code into your HTML

That gives you:

clean scalable graphics

easier color editing

no blurry image issues

What specifically makes a volleyball look real
If you are editing it manually, focus on these details:

1. Panel shape
A volleyball should have curved stitched-looking panels, not just random arcs.

2. Base color
Use slightly off-white shades:

#ffffff

#f3f3f0

#d0d0c8

3. Contrast
Your blue seams should vary a little:

darker main blue

slightly lighter secondary seam color

4. Lighting
A small highlight on the top-left and a shadow on the lower-right makes a huge difference.

5. Shadow under the object
Even if the ball itself is good, without shadow it still looks flat.

Small CSS improvement for your current ball
Even before changing the SVG, improve the container like this:

.volleyball {
  width: 340px;
  height: 340px;
  animation: floatBall 5s ease-in-out infinite;
  filter: drop-shadow(0 25px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.35));
}
That helps the ball feel more premium.

My recommendation
For your site, I’d do this:

keep it as inline SVG

replace the current simple drawing with a more realistic volleyball SVG

keep the floating animation

add stronger shadow and highlight

That gives the best balance of:

realism

performance

easy editing

good appearance on all screen sizes

I can also make you a better volleyball graphic already fitted into your exact homepage code so you can paste it directly.


